Explain diamonds model¶

The aim of this notebook is to model diamond prices with optimized Gradient Boosting and then explain the resulting model by SHAP, a concept borrowed from game theory. As such, the notebook can be used as a template for other regression situations.

Transform data¶

Before describing the data, we do two types of data transformations:

  • Clipping extreme values for carat, depth, and table

  • Reordering levels of categorical columns (color, cut, clarity)

In [8]:
from pandas.api.types import CategoricalDtype

# Function that prepares a pandas df line by line
#  -> handling of categories looks too verbose but allows (A) for safe preparation of a single line
#     and (B) for the right ordering of levels.

# Important variable groups
response = "price"
num_vars = ["carat", "depth", "table"]
ordinal_vars = ["color", "cut", "clarity"]
features = num_vars + ordinal_vars

def transform(df, select=features+[response]):
    df = df.assign(depth=df.depth.clip(50, 75),
                   table=df.table.clip(50, 70),
                   carat=df.carat.clip(upper=3),
                   color=pd.Categorical(df.color, categories=['D', 'E', 'F', 'G', 'H', 'I', 'J']),
                   cut=pd.Categorical(df.cut, categories=['Ideal', 'Premium', 'Very Good', 'Good', 'Fair']),
                   clarity=pd.Categorical(df.clarity, categories=['IF', 'VVS1', 'VVS2', 'VS1', 'VS2', 'SI1', 'SI2', 'I1']))
    return df[select]

df = transform(diamonds)

Prepare data for modeling¶

We will model the response by LightGBM, an extremely fast, open source gradient boosting implementation by Microsoft. Since its data interface allows only numeric columns, we replace categorical variables by their order index. For interpreting the models, we keep a version of the data with the original, human readable codings.

In [14]:
# Safe preprocessing with pandas
def ordinalCoder(df, ordinals=ordinal_vars):
    df = df.copy()
    df[ordinals] = df[ordinals].apply(lambda x: x.cat.codes)
    return df
    
# Response & features
y = df[response]
X_display = df[features]

# Integer coding
X = ordinalCoder(X_display)

print("Data structure for model:\n\n", X.head())
print("\nData structure for interpretation:\n\n", X_display.head())

Modeling¶

We now model the response as good as possible by the prepared features. For this purpose, we use a Gradient Boosting approach. Parameters are selected by iterative GridSearch with five-fold crossvalidation on 80% training data. The final model is then evaluated on the remaining 20% test data and compared with a Random Forest baseline model. Ideally, the tuned boosted trees do better than this benchmark.

The models are fitted by optimizing mean absolute deviance, i.e. using L1 loss as objective.

We start by splitting the data into train and test.

Data split¶

Tune model¶

In [17]:
tune = True

if tune:
    from sklearn.model_selection import ParameterSampler, ParameterGrid
    
    # Final narrow grid
    grid = ParameterSampler({
        "learning_rate": [0.02],
        "num_leaves": [20, 30, 40],
        'min_child_samples': [10, 15, 20],
        'reg_alpha': [0, 1, 2],
        'reg_lambda': [0, 1],
        'min_split_gain': [0, 0.001],
        'subsample': [0.9, 1],
        'bagging_freq': [1],
        'colsample_bytree': [1],
        'colsample_bynode': [1],
        "verbose": [2],
        "objective": ["regression_l1"],
        "metric": ["mae"],
        "nthread": [8] 
    }, n_iter=10)
    
    gridsearch_results = pd.DataFrame(columns=["params", "num_boost_round", "perf"])

    print("We are iterating through grid of size", len(grid))
    for g in grid:
        cv_results = lgb.cv(
            g,
            dtrain,
            num_boost_round=10000,
            nfold=5,
            stratified=False,
            early_stopping_rounds=20)
        perf = cv_results['l1-mean']
        new_row = {"params": [g], "num_boost_round": len(perf), "perf": perf[-1]}
        print(new_row)
        gridsearch_results = gridsearch_results.append(new_row, ignore_index=True)  
        gridsearch_results.to_json("gridsearch_results.txt")

Explain model¶

For model interpretation, we use SHAP. The idea of SHAP is to decompose single predictions into contributions from features as fair as possible. From these decompositions, variable importance and effects can be derived.

For an additive linear model, the SHAP contribution of the $j$th feature on the $i$th observation would agree with the product of the $j$th model coefficient and (centerd) $x_{ij}$.

In [22]:
import shap

# print the JS visualization code to the notebook
shap.initjs()

# Number of SHAP decompositions
N_SHAP = 2000 

# Initialize tree explainer
explainer = shap.TreeExplainer(model)

# Calculate N_SHAP decompositions
shap_values = explainer.shap_values(X_train[:N_SHAP])

Setting feature_perturbation = "tree_path_dependent" because no background data was given.

Illustration¶

For illustration of SHAP, we now decompose the first observation in the training data set into its SHAP components.

In [23]:
print("The original observation", X_display_train.iloc[0], sep="\n")
print("\nThe prediction walk")

shap.waterfall_plot(explainer.expected_value, shap_values[0], features=X_train.iloc[0])

print("\nThe reference price resp. average price:", explainer.expected_value)

The waterfall plot is read from bottom to top: Starting with the average diamond value of about 4000 USD, the prediction is positively impacted by its depth and clarity and negatively by table, cut and color. With a whopping two carats, the main boost in the prediction comes from the size (+12'7k).

Variable importance¶

In [24]:
shap.summary_plot(shap_values, X_train[:N_SHAP], plot_type="bar", color="Darkgreen")

Not surprisingly, the most important feature is the size of the carat. Next important is clarity, followed by the color. The other features are less intersing.

Effects plots¶

To get an impression on the effect of a feature $X$, we plot all contributions of $X$ against $X$. They are on the response scale but shifted by the reference price mentioned above.

In [25]:
sorted_cols = X_train.columns[np.argsort(-np.abs(shap_values).mean(0))]

for name in sorted_cols:
    shap.dependence_plot(name, shap_values, # + explainer.expected_value, 
                         X_train[:N_SHAP], display_features=X_display_train[:N_SHAP], 
                         show=False, alpha=0.25, dot_size=4, x_jitter=0.2, 
                         xmin="percentile(1)", xmax="percentile(99)")
    plt.title(f"{name}", fontdict={'fontsize': 16, 'weight': 'bold'})
